# Pharmacy Saas - Coding Conventions

## Architecture rules

- Layered: UI (PMS.Desktop) -> Service (PMS.Services) -> Repository / EF DbContext / Dapper (PMS.Data) -> SQL Server
- UI never touches DbContext or repositories directly. Always go through a service.
- Services live in PMS.Services; abstractions live in PMS.Core/Abstractions.
- Cross-cutting concerns (hashing, encryption, fingerprint, license signing) live in PMS.Security.

## Database rules

- Every table is prefixed `tbl_`.
- Every operational table includes:
  - `Id INT IDENTITY PRIMARY KEY`
  - `RecordGuid UNIQUEIDENTIFIER NOT NULL DEFAULT NEWID()` (sync key)
  - Audit fields: `IsActive`, `SaveDate`, `SavedBy`, `UpdatedDate`, `UpdatedBy`
  - `IsSynced BIT NOT NULL DEFAULT 0` where the row participates in sync
  - `BranchId INT NULL FK tbl_Branches(Id)` where multi-branch matters
- Schema changes ship as numbered SQL scripts (`00X_*.sql`) in PMS.Database/Scripts and are applied idempotently by `SqlScriptRunner` on app start. `tbl_SchemaVersion` tracks applied scripts.
- Soft-delete only - never hard delete a domain row. Admin recycle bin (`tbl_RecycleBin`) restores.

## Service rules

- Every mutation must call `IAuditService.LogAsync(...)`.
- Every UI screen must check `IPermissionService.CanAccessAsync(module, permission)` and `IPermissionService.IsModuleEnabledAsync(pharmacy, module)`.
- Use `IClock` for `DateTime.UtcNow` so we can fake time in tests.
- Hot paths (POS, reports) use Dapper via `IDbConnectionFactory`. Admin / setup / CRUD uses EF Core (`PharmacyDbContext`).

## Security rules

- Never store plaintext passwords. Use `IPasswordHasher` (BCrypt-backed).
- Never construct `AesGcm` directly outside `AesEncryptionService`.
- License files are encrypted + signed; the signature MUST be verified on every read.
- Audit every security event (login success/failure, license create/renew, machine register/replace, password change, role change, backup restore).

## UI rules

- WPF + MVVM via CommunityToolkit.Mvvm (`[ObservableProperty]`, `[RelayCommand]`).
- No business logic in event handlers / code-behind. Code-behind only bridges things WPF cannot bind (e.g. `PasswordBox.Password`).
- Reuse `IDialogService` for messages; never call `MessageBox.Show` directly from view models.
- Theme tokens live in `Theme/Colors.xaml`; no inline hex colors in views.

## Naming

- Project namespaces: `PMS.<Layer>` (e.g. `PMS.Services`, `PMS.Security`).
- Async methods always end in `Async` and return `Task` / `Task<T>`.
- Interfaces start with `I`. Constants live in static classes under `PMS.Core/Constants`.
- Permission keys, module keys, role keys come from `PMS.Core.Constants` - do not hardcode strings.

## Module / phase discipline

- Phase gates are enforced. No medicines/sales/purchases/reports code in Phase 1.
- New features added behind a module flag (`tbl_ModuleSettings`) when the blueprint marks them gated.
- License tier mapping (Basic/Standard/Premium) lives in `LicenseService`, not scattered.
